{"author":{"id":"729f4229091d502775e0e5c4bfc138609955b348584d955f4229a3d76892d2a9"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1479372053,"nonce":"FRWaJNXspmJm9eXcQRhMgS5vk4M=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxODk5NzY4Njg=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1041","origin":"github"},"title":"hisat2 output fastq files of unaligned reads?","message":"This request is inspired by [this post](https://biostar.usegalaxy.org/p/20551/) on the biostars site (and the fact that it's only a matter of time before one of our post-docs asks for this). It'd be nice if the hisat2 wrapper supported the `--un-conc` and `--un` options. In experiments like ribosomal profiling, you end up with a LOT of rRNA and small non-coding RNAs that are basically just nuisance species. At the command line, we get rid of these by making a fasta file with rRNA and the other things in it, align everything against that, and then just continue with the reads that don't align. I presume that the \"remove rRNA using bowtie\" on RiboGalaxy is working in a similar way, but of course it'd be nice to not need a separate tool that's not in the main toolshed for this.\n\nAs always, since I'm making the request, I'm happy to implement it if the IUC supports the idea.","files":null}]}